1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,820
The Hypertext Markup Language or HTML,

2
00:00:02,820 --> 00:00:06,000
is the language used to create documents for the worldwide web,

3
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:09,660
and you've likely encountered it hundreds of thousands of times without knowing.

4
00:00:09,660 --> 00:00:12,510
Let's dive into the structure of an HTML file to better

5
00:00:12,510 --> 00:00:16,245
understand how data wranglers extract value from these files.

6
00:00:16,245 --> 00:00:18,780
HTML is just a collection of tags.

7
00:00:18,780 --> 00:00:22,905
The label inside the angle brackets indicates the type of elements,

8
00:00:22,905 --> 00:00:26,635
for example, in the highlighted box this is a title tag.

9
00:00:26,635 --> 00:00:31,010
The content between the tags is generally what people will see in the browser.

10
00:00:31,010 --> 00:00:32,360
The title of this webpage,

11
00:00:32,360 --> 00:00:34,615
for example, is HTML structure.

12
00:00:34,615 --> 00:00:38,090
Note how the first mention of the title tag is an angled brackets,

13
00:00:38,090 --> 00:00:42,680
but the second mention after the HTML structure texts has an angle bracket,

14
00:00:42,680 --> 00:00:44,600
a slash, the word title,

15
00:00:44,600 --> 00:00:46,400
and then a closing angle bracket.

16
00:00:46,400 --> 00:00:50,780
This second mention of title with a slash indicates that this is the end of the tag.

17
00:00:50,780 --> 00:00:53,680
So the rest of the HTML isn't the full title,

18
00:00:53,680 --> 00:00:56,695
it's just the words between the title tags.

19
00:00:56,695 --> 00:00:59,465
There are different types of HTML elements.

20
00:00:59,465 --> 00:01:02,510
Heading elements are used for section heading tags,

21
00:01:02,510 --> 00:01:05,480
such as H1, H2, H3, and H4.

22
00:01:05,480 --> 00:01:09,155
Paragraph elements are used for standard blocks of texts.

23
00:01:09,155 --> 00:01:13,175
Image elements are used to embed images in a webpage,

24
00:01:13,175 --> 00:01:15,380
and span elements are used to

25
00:01:15,380 --> 00:01:18,575
group text within another block of texts, often for styling.

26
00:01:18,575 --> 00:01:20,585
Let's take a look at two examples.

27
00:01:20,585 --> 00:01:24,080
The first example you can see that this is a span texts looks

28
00:01:24,080 --> 00:01:27,770
just like as if it had been placed in a P or a paragraph tag,

29
00:01:27,770 --> 00:01:30,895
but without the extra blank line before and after.

30
00:01:30,895 --> 00:01:32,735
For the second span tag,

31
00:01:32,735 --> 00:01:35,900
we can change the style of the another span text.

32
00:01:35,900 --> 00:01:38,510
We can define the color as red in hexadecimal.

33
00:01:38,510 --> 00:01:41,270
Now, you can see in the webpage snippet on the right,

34
00:01:41,270 --> 00:01:43,760
the another span text is red.

35
00:01:43,760 --> 00:01:47,525
The head element contains metadata about the webpage,

36
00:01:47,525 --> 00:01:49,580
like the page's title or its encoding,

37
00:01:49,580 --> 00:01:51,920
in this case, UTF-8.

38
00:01:51,920 --> 00:01:55,040
The body element contains the actual HTML,

39
00:01:55,040 --> 00:01:56,300
which is where all the tags,

40
00:01:56,300 --> 00:01:58,775
such as heading in paragraph tags take place.

41
00:01:58,775 --> 00:02:04,745
The HTML tag is a container for all other HTML elements except for the doc-type tag.

42
00:02:04,745 --> 00:02:07,430
All HTML files must start with

43
00:02:07,430 --> 00:02:09,470
this doctype HTML tag to give

44
00:02:09,470 --> 00:02:12,905
information to the browser that they should expect an HTML file.

45
00:02:12,905 --> 00:02:18,245
Let's compare HTML files with a couple of popular file formats, starting with JSON.

46
00:02:18,245 --> 00:02:22,940
JSON and HTML are similar in that you can have elements inside of elements,

47
00:02:22,940 --> 00:02:24,995
but that's where the similarities end.

48
00:02:24,995 --> 00:02:29,720
We can create a tree structure in HTML by putting elements inside elements.

49
00:02:29,720 --> 00:02:33,545
To do this, we often use a div element as a container.

50
00:02:33,545 --> 00:02:38,510
Div elements are used to group chunks of content together such as these H1 and P tags.

51
00:02:38,510 --> 00:02:40,040
As you write HTML code,

52
00:02:40,040 --> 00:02:44,890
the hierarchy that you can create can grow as wide or as deep as you need them to be.

53
00:02:44,890 --> 00:02:48,375
HTML and JSON are used for different purposes.

54
00:02:48,375 --> 00:02:50,375
HTML is used for building websites,

55
00:02:50,375 --> 00:02:53,165
whereas JSON is used for communicating information,

56
00:02:53,165 --> 00:02:54,815
for example through APIs.

57
00:02:54,815 --> 00:02:57,755
JSON is capable of handling more complex data,

58
00:02:57,755 --> 00:03:00,475
whereas HTML has a simpler structure.

59
00:03:00,475 --> 00:03:05,090
HTML files have a much more complicated structure though compared to flat files.

60
00:03:05,090 --> 00:03:09,470
For example, consider a short review written for the archive.org book item.

61
00:03:09,470 --> 00:03:14,090
You can see how on the left the content is nestled within the different HTML elements,

62
00:03:14,090 --> 00:03:15,605
including the reviewer name,

63
00:03:15,605 --> 00:03:19,865
the stars, the subject of the review, and the content.

64
00:03:19,865 --> 00:03:23,705
On the right, take a look at a flat file with the same content with the columns,

65
00:03:23,705 --> 00:03:26,525
reviewer, stars, subject, and texts.

66
00:03:26,525 --> 00:03:29,570
We would need to pass the HTML file on the left and

67
00:03:29,570 --> 00:03:34,410
extract the information accordingly to get it into the format on the right.

